{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"70852195-8f67-4c89-bc9f-b91ad3239e54","content":"No existing files found. Here's how to convert your page to compiled bindings:\n\n**Add `x:DataType` to your ContentPage:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\">\n\n    <VerticalStackLayout>\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding Theme}\" />\n        <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding FontSize}\" />\n    </VerticalStackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe key change is `x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\"` — this tells the XAML compiler the type of `BindingContext`, enabling compile-time resolution of all `{Binding}` expressions on the page.\n\n**To catch binding errors at build time**, add this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n    <MauiStrictXamlCompilation>true</MauiStrictXamlCompilation>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis promotes XAML binding warnings (e.g., misspelled property names like `{Binding Themee}`) to **build errors**.\n\n**Key points:**\n- Any `{Binding}` referencing a property not on `SettingsViewModel` will fail at compile time.\n- If a child element binds to a different type, use a local `x:DataType` override on that element.\n- To opt out for a specific binding (e.g., a `BindingContext` assignment), use `x:DataType=\"\"` to disable compiled bindings locally.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7b5e188a-c95a-4898-af58-002b7af7dd35","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"D44F:27A376:1C7F83A:200BFD3:6A07C0AD"},"id":"22abb247-29fe-4668-9683-a6a0b2809d17","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:56:22.136Z","parentId":"3b2957b4-c028-49cc-b211-19ed693a9e78"}
